Chapter 9. Tidy data with tidyr

Tidy data

Q1

Each variable should be put in a seperate volumn, and observations are arranged in rows.

Q2

table2:

cases <- table2 %>%
  group_by(country, year) %>%
  filter(type == "cases") %>%
  rename(cases = count)
population <- table2 %>%
  group_by(country, year) %>%
  filter(type == "population") %>%
  rename(population = count)
table2.1 <- tibble(country = cases$ country, year = cases$year, cases = cases$cases, population = population$population) %>%
  mutate(rate = cases / population * 10000)
table2.1
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   country      year  cases population  rate
##   <chr>       <int>  <int>      <int> <dbl>
## 1 Afghanistan  1999    745   19987071 0.373
## 2 Afghanistan  2000   2666   20595360 1.29 
## 3 Brazil       1999  37737  172006362 2.19 
## 4 Brazil       2000  80488  174504898 4.61 
## 5 China        1999 212258 1272915272 1.67 
## 6 China        2000 213766 1280428583 1.67

table4a & 4b:

table4.1 <- tibble(country = table4a$country, "1999rate" = table4a[['1999']] / table4b[['1999']] * 10000, "2000rate" = table4a[['2000']] / table4b[['2000']] * 10000)
table4.1
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   country     `1999rate` `2000rate`
##   <chr>            <dbl>      <dbl>
## 1 Afghanistan      0.373       1.29
## 2 Brazil           2.19        4.61
## 3 China            1.67        1.67

The table4a and 4b one is slightly easier, since we don’t need to generate a new tibble to store the data.

Q3

table2 %>%
  filter(type == "cases") %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, count)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = country)) +
  geom_line(aes(group = country, color = "grey50"))

We need to find out the values of cases first.

Gathering and spreading

Q1

stocks <- tibble(
year =c(2015,2015,2016,2016), half=c(1, 2, 1, 2), return = c(1.88, 0.59, 0.92, 0.17)
)
stocks
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##    year  half return
##   <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  2015     1   1.88
## 2  2015     2   0.59
## 3  2016     1   0.92
## 4  2016     2   0.17
stocks1 <- spread(stocks, key = half, value = return)
stocks1
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##    year   `1`   `2`
##   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1  2015  1.88  0.59
## 2  2016  0.92  0.17
stocks1 %>%
  gather(key = "half", value = "return",  '1', '2')
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##    year half  return
##   <dbl> <chr>  <dbl>
## 1  2015 1       1.88
## 2  2016 1       0.92
## 3  2015 2       0.59
## 4  2016 2       0.17

The data type of the column is lost (half change from dbl to chr)

stocks %>%
  spread(key = "half", value = "return") %>%
  gather('1', '2', key = "half", value = "return", convert = TRUE)
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##    year  half return
##   <dbl> <int>  <dbl>
## 1  2015     1   1.88
## 2  2016     1   0.92
## 3  2015     2   0.59
## 4  2016     2   0.17

Convert turns the half to integers. Convert guesses the data type.

Q2

You need to add “” around the 1999 and 2000 so that they can be interpreted as names.

Q3

people <- tribble(
  ~name, ~key, ~value,
  #-----------------|--------|------
  "Phillip Woods", "age", 45,
  "Phillip Woods", "height", 186,
  "Phillip Woods", "age", 50,
  "Jessica Cordero", "age", 37,
  "Jessica Cordero", "height", 156
)

spread(people, key, value) There are two values corresponding to Phillip Woods’ age.

people1 <- people %>%
  group_by(name, key) %>%
  mutate(obs = row_number())
people1
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
## # Groups:   name, key [4]
##   name            key    value   obs
##   <chr>           <chr>  <dbl> <int>
## 1 Phillip Woods   age       45     1
## 2 Phillip Woods   height   186     1
## 3 Phillip Woods   age       50     2
## 4 Jessica Cordero age       37     1
## 5 Jessica Cordero height   156     1
spread(people1, key, value)
## # A tibble: 3 x 4
## # Groups:   name [2]
##   name              obs   age height
##   <chr>           <int> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 Jessica Cordero     1    37    156
## 2 Phillip Woods       1    45    186
## 3 Phillip Woods       2    50     NA

preg <- tribble(
~pregnant, ~male, ~female, "yes", NA, 10, "no", 20, 12
)
preg

##   pregnant  male female
##   <chr>    <dbl>  <dbl>

## 2 no          20     12
preg1 <- preg %>%
  gather(male, female, key = "sex", value ="count")

Separate and unite

Q1

tibble(x = c("a,b,c", "d,e,f,g", "h,i,j")) %>%
    separate(x, c("one", "two", "three"), extra = "merge")
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   one   two   three
##   <chr> <chr> <chr>
## 1 a     b     c    
## 2 d     e     f,g  
## 3 h     i     j

Extra: default is dropping the extra piece and giving a warning = “drop”: simply drop the values = “merge”: put the extras into the last column.

tibble(x = c("a,b,c", "d,e", "f,g,i")) %>%
    separate(x, c("one", "two", "three"), fill = "left")
## # A tibble: 3 x 3
##   one   two   three
##   <chr> <chr> <chr>
## 1 a     b     c    
## 2 <NA>  d     e    
## 3 f     g     i

Fill: when there is not enought pieces default is give a warning and fill from the right with NA. = “right”: fill from the right = “left”: fill from the left

Q2

table5 %>%
    unite(Year, century, year, sep = "", remove = F)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   country     Year  century year  rate             
##   <chr>       <chr> <chr>   <chr> <chr>            
## 1 Afghanistan 1999  19      99    745/19987071     
## 2 Afghanistan 2000  20      00    2666/20595360    
## 3 Brazil      1999  19      99    37737/172006362  
## 4 Brazil      2000  20      00    80488/174504898  
## 5 China       1999  19      99    212258/1272915272
## 6 China       2000  20      00    213766/1280428583

“remove” removes the input values from the table. When you want to keep the old variables you can set it to FALSE.

Q3

separate() split a column by identifying the separator, while extract() split a column by identifying the entry as following a general form with some groups within. Because you can choose how to divide a column, but when uniting you can only choose the type of sepearator to put between.

Missing Values

Q1

stocks %>%
  spread(year, return, fill = "N")
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##    half `2015` `2016`
##   <dbl> <chr>  <chr> 
## 1     1 1.88   0.92  
## 2     2 0.59   0.17
stocks %>%
  complete(year, fill = list("N","A"))
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##    year  half return
##   <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  2015     1   1.88
## 2  2015     2   0.59
## 3  2016     1   0.92
## 4  2016     2   0.17

it can fill a list in the complete()

Q2

stocks %>%
  fill(return, .direction = "up")
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##    year  half return
##   <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  2015     1   1.88
## 2  2015     2   0.59
## 3  2016     1   0.92
## 4  2016     2   0.17

It specify whether to fill NA with the previous or next value.

WHO Case Study

Q1

who %>%
  filter(new_sp_m014 == 0) %>%
  nrow()
## [1] 862

There is 0 cases. So missing value (NA) probably doesn’t mean 0 case occurs for that category; it means WHO don’t have the data. Thus it’s reasonable to ignore it.

select(who1, country, iso2, iso3) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  filter(n() > 1)
## # A tibble: 0 x 3
## # Groups:   country [0]
## # ... with 3 variables: country <chr>, iso2 <chr>, iso3 <chr>

There is no distinct combination of iso2 and iso3 for each country, so iso2 and iso3 are indeed only abbr.

Q4

who2 <- who1 %>%
  group_by(country, year, sex) %>%
  summarise(cases = sum(cases)) %>%
  unite(countrysex, country, sex, remove = F) %>%
  filter(year > 1995) 
ggplot(who2, aes(x = year, y = cases, group = countrysex, colour = sex)) +
  geom_line()

Chapter 10 Relational Data with dplyr

nycflights13

Q1

flights and airports; flights give you the flights of plane and its departing and arriving airports, while airports gives the longitude and latitude of those airports. origin&dest in flights and faa&lat&lon in airports.

Q2

origin in weather –> faa in airports

Q3

origin in weather –> dest in flights, both share time.

Q4

holidays <- tribble(
  ~name, ~year, ~month, ~day,
  "New year", 2013, 01, 01, 
  "July 4th", 2013, 07, 04, 
  "Thanksgiving", 2013, 11, 29,
  "Chrismas", 2013, 12, 25
)

Date and name. Date can be used to map to existing tables.
